    <summary>Specifies when a <see cref="T:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule" /> runs.</summary>
    <remarks>
      <format type="text/markdown"><![CDATA[  
  
## Examples  
 The following example uses a <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule> named `ValidateDateAndPrice`. The <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.ValidationStep%2A> for this rule is set to ConvertedProposedValue so that when it runs, the <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.Validate%2A> method has access to values that are of the source property's type.  
  
 When the `PriceIsAPositiveNumber` and `FutureDateRule` rules run, the values in each <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.Validate%2A> method are strings because the default value of <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.ValidationStep%2A> is RawProposedValue. Therefore, the rules run before the values are converted to their respective types.  
  
 [!code-xaml[BindingGroupSnippets#WindowLayout](~/samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_Wpf/BindingGroupSnippets/CSharp/Window1.xaml#windowlayout)]  
  
 The following example shows the `ValidateDateAndPrice`<xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.ValidationStep%2A>. In the <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule.Validate%2A> method, the `Price` property is of type <xref:System.Double> and the `OfferExpires` property is of type <xref:System.DateTime>. The strings have been converted to their respective types by the time the <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ValidationRule> runs.  
  
